As the rite of confirmation, is thus ſanctioned by the holy ſcriptures, and the general practice of churches of Chriſt, in all ages; as it is, in itſelf, moſt rational, and calculated to be


productive of very happy effects, we cannot, therefore, but applaud the piety and wiſdom of the church of England, at the time of the reformation, in retaining this inſtitution;


after having ſeparated from it, every practice that was offenſive, or ſuperſtitious.
